This battle, as well as that of Cul-Dremhne, was between the Northern and Seuthem branches of the Hy Neill. It was fought by Aedh, son of Ainmire, to avenge the death of Baedan, son of Ninnidh, monarch of Ireland, who had been slain by Cumine, son of Colman Beg, and his second cousin Cumine, son of Libran, at Leim- in-eieh, under the instigation of Colman Beg. How far St. Columba participated in this transaction is not recorded, but that he was deeply interested in it appeffls evident from the words of Tighernach, a sentiment which tho Four Masters studiously sup- press.
